ce:section.ce:para:
Through the nano-precipitation process, the nanoparticles of CPNs-NH2 were obtained base on of conjugated polymer (PBOC) and PEI. They were dissolved in water with a yellow color under natural light (Fig. 1c) and the orange-yellow fluorescence under ultraviolet light (Fig. 1e). Fig. 1a–I displayed that CPNs-NH2 (25 μg/mL) has a strong UV absorption peak at about 430 nm. The fluorescence spectrum (Fig. 1a-Ⅱ) obtained at 430 nm showed that CPNs-NH2 has an apparent fluorescence emission peak at 545 nm. The side peaks at 460 nm and 510 nm were proved to belong to CPNs-NH2 itself, and the details were described in support information (Fig. S1). The optimal ratio of PBOC and PEI was determined by a series of experiments. TEM image (Fig. 2a) shows that the nanoparticles have an uneven size (20–40 nm) at the mole ratio of PBOC: PEI = 5:1. The obvious brightness of CPNs-NH2 sample in TEM image is because we chose the copper mesh of carbon film material. As a polymer material, CPNs-NH2 is easy to be passed through by electron beam relative to carbon film. Thus, the background of TEM image is deep and the sample is bright. Dynamic light Scattering (DLS) data can also prove this (Fig. 2d). The reason could be understood as that only a part of PBOC was connected with PEI, and the other of PBOC curled into nanoparticles, resulting in uneven size. When the ratio of PBOC: PEI was promoted to 5:3, the size of nanoparticles was still uneven from 30 nm to 60 nm (Fig. 2c). It can be viewed intuitively from DLS data (Fig. 2f). The reason was that the surface of PBOC could combine with multiple PEI at the same time, resulting in the generation of large-size nanoparticles. The morphology of CPNs-NH2 was nearly spherical excellent uniformity (Fig. 2b) at the ratio of PBOC: PEI = 5:2, which showed this ratio was the best choice (Fig. 2e). In addition, the nanoparticles of CPNs-NH2 (1 μg/mL) have Zeta potentials of 19.8 mV (Fig. 3
                           d
                           ).
